item.title: Getting Back to Nature in a Canoe
item.dc:creator: MIKAEL SHAMSIE
item.content:encoded:
It’s easy to get lost in the insanity of modern life. Meetings, places to be, work to do, more meetings, parties, family and friends—it’s an endless cycle of expectations and pressures. It’s almost too much to fit into your schedule, and yet you do again and again, day after day, week after week. You might not notice it moment to moment, but that continuous struggle, that endless grind, is wearing away at you. Luckily, there is a remedy.

That remedy comes in the form of a distinct sense of peace, a certain sense of liberation, that comes with setting all that aside. Not only setting it aside but also leaving behind your environment and your familiar surroundings and delving into nature. And there are few activities that reconnect you to nature like canoeing. Just you, a small vessel, a single paddle and a seemingly infinite mass of untroubled water stretching out before you. Inviting you to leisurely paddle to your heart’s content.

The soft sounds of water parting with each stroke of your paddle. The caress of a gentle gust of wind. The warmth of sunrays pushing their way past fluffy clouds. The crystal blue water reflecting the heavens all around you. The sudden realization that you’ve been yearning for this all along. That is what strikes you when you return to the ineffable allure of the wild. It brings with it beauty and serenity that words can only express a glimmer of. You have to find out for yourself to understand. Go. Get back to it.

item.title: Taking in the View at Big Mountain
item.dc:creator: MIKAEL SHAMSIE
item.content:encoded:
Upon ascending the unforgiving slopes of Big Mountain, sweat tickling your brow, an unwavering sense of accomplishment can grip you. The release of endorphins triggered by the exercise can further bolster this feeling. Yet, one glance down at the world below and all that is wiped away, leaving only awe.

There are certain experiences in this life that immediately rearrange your sense of self, the world and your place in it. Even if you’re not conscious of it, even if you can’t put it into words, you feel it in your bones. In that moment, as you gaze upon the world below, looking so small, so indistinct and yet so magnificent, you are elevated – you know that you are a part of something bigger and, in that, you find, when the awe settles, a sense of peace.

For regular life there’s meditation or prayer or a quiet moment of contemplation. All valuable tools for finding tranquillity, and all fall well short of the raw emotion driven home by the sight of the world laid bare hundreds of metres below you. In that rarified air, with only clouds for company, you stand exalted—at the highest of highs, both literally and emotionally.

With rivers reduced to rivulets, forests diminished to shrubbery, hills shrunk into knolls and humanity reduced to indistinguishable specks, knowing you, too, are one of those specks, you lose your sense of self. No longer burdened by the abundance of pressures your mind normally inflicts upon you, you stand. Free.

item.title: Star-Gazing at the Night Sky
item.dc:creator: MIKAEL SHAMSIE
item.content:encoded:
In a cloudless night sky, wonders can be gazed upon. From Orion’s belt to the North Star, dazzling marvels of nature are displayed above you, inviting your awe. Whether it’s from the lofty perch of an observation deck or from on your back lying in your sleeping bag in the wilderness, celestial majesty awaits from above if only you choose to look.

In our daily trials and tribulations, we lose our connection with the sense of unknown and grandeur that exists all around us, especially that of the cosmos. That connection is forged anew with just one clear look up. And it comes with a much-needed dose of perspective. We are, after all, finite beings, pieces of inorganic matter, on a blue dot, hurtling through space, destined to only know a tiny fraction of the mysteries of life and nature. In the face of that, the exigencies of our regular lives may seem a little less overwhelming and a little more manageable. Maybe, in the face of our infinitesimally small place in the universe, there’s a lot in our lives that we can come to handle with a little more grace. 

With each flash in the night sky. With each sparkle from the ocean of gems that populate the heavens, know amazement and, with it, know reverence and appreciation for your unique position in the midst of it. With those feelings in your heart, that squabble you had at work might appear far less important an occurrence. And that grudge you’re holding, much easier to let go of. And that person you care for, much easier to love and hold. That is the wonder of the night sky. Beauty. Majesty. Perspective. Only one good gaze away.

item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: Jorrin Bruns
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:
Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Halifax, have a great dog named Jack, and I like . (And gettin' caught in the rain.)
...or something like this:
The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.
As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: Jorrin Bruns
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Our website address is: //localhost:3000/wordpress.

What personal data we collect and why we collect it

Comments

When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Contact forms

Cookies

If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you have an account and you log in to this site, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Analytics

Who we share your data with

How long we retain your data

If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where we send your data

Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.
